President Joe Biden addressed a gathering at the White House to celebrate Asian American, Native Hawaiian, and Pacific Islander Heritage Month. He praised the accomplishments of the Asian American community, including Ke Huy Quan, an actor who won an Oscar for his role in the movie "Everything Everywhere All At Once." Biden also highlighted the diversity within his administration and the importance of inclusivity in government. He discussed the ongoing challenges of racism and hate crimes faced by the community and pledged to take action to combat them. Biden also addressed the issue of gun violence and his efforts to implement stricter gun control measures. He emphasized the importance of storytelling and the power of diversity in shaping the nation's identity. The President concluded his speech by expressing his belief in the potential for positive change and the need to ensure that every aspect of the country reflects the diversity of America.